title: For Sale:  NIB CZ527 Varmint in .223
postcontent:
Up for sale is a CZ527 Varmint rifle in .223 Remington. It is equipped with a 1" Leupold VX-3 2.5-8x36mm with duplex reticle. The CZ527 has a tapered bull barrel and a 1:12 rate of twist designed for lighter .233 ammunition. The rifle has a single-set trigger with allows the shooter to remove all but 1lb from the trigger pull which makes it a highly accurate firearm. I built it as my coyote rifle after many months of research and found that most owners report sub-MOA out of the box to several hundred yards. I can't attest to this claim personally because I've never fired the rifle - my hunting buddy deployed to Afghanistan and now I have no use for it. 

Included in the sale are two snapcaps, 1 detachable 5-round magazine, 120 rounds of 40gr Hornady V-Max ammo (reportedly the most accurate ammo for this rifle), a custom bolt handle (the factory handle wouldn't clear the rear bell of a scope), the never-used aforementioned Leupold, and a pair of Warne rings. It's a perfect setup for any varmint hunter or someone just looking for an exceptionally accurate target rifle. 

The above items cost me over $1500, plus taxes. I'd like $1300 for it and am open to certain partial trades. Acceptable trades would be a blued Sig P232, Walther PPK in .32ACP, IZH-35M, or other interesting boutique firearms.

title: For Sale:  Eclipse Double Barrel, 12 gage, dog ear hammers.
postcontent:
Eclipse Double Barrel, 12 gage, dog ear hammers. Serial #54xxx. 

This is a WALL HANGER, not safe to shoot! A couple of small dents in the barrels and a Damascus barrel!  

In addition there is a crack in the stock just behind the receiver. Marked #5212 D OXFORD.IM. DAMASCUS BELGIM CHOKED. 30 inch barrel. 

The Eclipse Gun Co name was owned (trademarked to) Henri Pieper of Belgium and guns were manufactured from as early as the 1880's to as late as the 1920's. Henri Pieper was associated with several different companies some of which bore his name and all of them made handguns and shotguns. The Eclipse Gun Co. models ranged from a low of $14 to a high of $60 in the 1907 era. Ithaca doubles of that era ranged from $17.50 to $112.50. The Eclipse Gun Co. models were good quality, dependable, field grade doubles. Many models were made with Damascus barrels as were many of the quality doubles of the era. The 1907 Iver Johnson catalog had two pages on Eclipse Gun Co. models (6 total). This catalog fully identifies these guns as being of Pieper manufacture. The Eclipse Gun Company was also the trade name for guns imported by E.C. Meacham and by The W.C. George companies and the guns were made by Anciens Establishments Pieper, the Belgium gun maker founded by Henri Pieper. The company survived until 1957. Located in Davison. No trades, cash only

title: For Sale:  Rare French MAS MLE 1949 - 56 in 7.5 mm - Nice 49/56
postcontent:
Here is a very seldom seen assult rifle.  A French MAS MLE 1949-56 rifle in original 7.5 mm.  

The predecessor rifle was the French MAS-49; it was formally adopted by the French Army in July 1949. 

An improved version of the MAS-49 was the MAS-49/56; it was introduced in 1957 and incorporated lessons learned from service in Algeria, Indochina, and the Suez Crisis. The rifle was shortened and lightened to improve mobility for mechanized and airborne troops, and a knife bayonet was added. The MAS-49 built-in rifle grenade launcher was replaced by a combination compensator/rifle grenade launcher that fired NATO-standard 22mm rifle grenades. The rifle also incorporates an integral grenade launching sight that is attached to the front sight block and a gas cutoff that prevents gas from entering the gas tube from the gas port when firing grenade launching blank ammunition.

This rifle is chambered in the original 7.5 mm; many were re-chambered at import into .308 and are considered less desirable. 

This rifle is excellent overall condition. Tight bolt action, clean barrel, and nice rifling. The stock in very good condition (see pictures).  

Again, weapon is in original 7.5 X 54 (French) or 7.5 mm, and also has the original barrel length at approximately 20.7". 

Original 10 round clip included. 

This is a unique opportunity to own a fairly rare rifle in excellent condition.  

 Please call or text for more information, or more pictures (15+).

title: For Sale:  1941 Springfield M1 Garand + Bayonet + Ammo
postcontent:
Beautiful example of an early Garand. This Springfield was built in July of 1941 with a serial number in the 297,xxx range. It then went through a re-arsenal in Dec. 1965 at the Letterkenny Arsenal Army Depot. Has appropriate LEAD mark on receiver and the arsenal stamp is still intact on the stock as well (Hard to find the stocks with correct re-arsenal stamp since it can rub off). The barrel they put on in the re-arsenal is marked 1956 and there are no import marks on this rifle. Unfortunately I don't have gauges to put a number on the throat wear and muzzle but judging by a 30-06 round in the muzzle it's no worse than 1.5 and probably closer to 1. Chamber looks good though and it shoots fine so I can't imagine there is any excessive throat wear. 

Included with the rifle is a 1942 bayonet and a bandolier with surplus ammo on enblocs. (7 clips w/8 rounds each for 56 rounds total)

The sling pictured is actually an M1 carbine sling but was on the rifle when I received it in trade and I never got around to swapping it out. It will be included with the rifle. I don't have a photo of the bayonet but it is a model 1905E1 which is basically a 1942 bayonet that was cut down during the war to a 10" length from it's original 16" length. Comes with scabbard.
